Job Description:
The Georgia Department of Behavioral Health and Developmental Disabilities (DBHDD) is the state agency that focuses solely on policies, programs, and services for people with mental health challenges, substance use disorders, intellectual and developmental disabilities, or any combination of these. As Georgia’s public safety net, DBHDD operates six field offices and five hospitals throughout the state within three program areas: behavioral health, developmental disabilities and hospital services.



The main office for DBHDD is located in downtown Atlanta.



Job Description


Job Title: Performance Analyst


Pay Grade: L


Job Summary:



The Performance Analyst will be responsible for the following:

Assisting in the development of appropriate study protocols, research designs, and statistical analyses;
Consulting with internal and external clients to determine questions of interest, appropriate analytical designs, and data necessary to address those questions related to determining program performance and outcomes analysis;
Establishing and maintaining effective working relationships with individuals inside and outside OPAQI, especially the programmatic divisions to support and be an expert for program evaluation and other scientifically-based projects;
Demonstrating leadership qualities, creative and strategic thinking, and individual contributions;
Developing and analyzing a variety of data using statistical methods and carrying out appropriate statistical analysis, including the following:
Building of complex statistical models to determine system- and program-level performance, as well as outcomes and indications of what key variables may be leveraged to increase performance or enhance outcomes;
Forecasting of system needs using different sources of data from national, state, and local resources;
Conducting simulation and what-if changes to existing systems to support decision making;
Support in conducting or technical expert for network analysis of the community behavioral health and intellectual/developmental disabilities systems;
Evaluation of systems of care, including what is working and what changes may be indicated by data;
Using data illustration and data visualization software to build different models and dashboards for various audiences to provide data insights to answer pertinent questions for the users;
Interpreting and presenting data and analysis in multiple ways, including the explanation of statistical techniques used, the assumptions made, and the generalizability of results;
Documenting methods and results through preparation of interdepartmental memoranda, manuscripts, presentations, and reports;
Application of logical thought to new situations/analyses;
Responsible for identifying, analysis/critique/review of extant research literature to inform the design, execution, analysis, and reporting of research studies as needed.



Minimum Qualifications

Advanced degree (Master’s/Doctorate) in statistics, biostatistics, epidemiology, public/business/health administration, social/behavioral or health science, program evaluation analysis or closely related field with significant coursework and experience involving advanced statistical analysis;
Facility with statistical analysis software packages (e.g., R, SAS, SPSS, LISREL, etc.);
Three or more years of experience in statistical analysis including applying statistical analytical tools such as measurement modeling, measurement of central tendency, dispersion, skewness, data transformation, sampling error, multiple correlation, analysis of variance, tests of significance, regression analysis, time series modeling, generalized linear modeling, sample size and power analysis, etc.;
Working effectively within group settings in areas of design of data collection instruments, study design, database management, statistical programming, analysis of data, statistical graphics, and report writing for technical and lay audiences;
Strong analytical reasoning and problem-solving abilities and project management skills and experience, including success in large data analytic projects;
Excellent communication skills and the ability to establish and maintain effective and productive working relationships with multiple offices and divisions;
Proficiency with Microsoft Office Suite Software including Outlook, Word, Excel, PowerPoint, and OneNote. Willingness and ability to learn, adopt and utilize new computer technology and software skills;
Ability to communicate effectively with non-statisticians to interpret and communicate statistical and research findings.



Preferred Qualifications

Preference will be given to candidates who, in addition to meeting the qualifications listed above, possess the following:

Doctorate in statistics, biostatistics, epidemiology, public/business/health administration, social/behavioral or health science, program evaluation analysis or closely-related field with a significant coursework and experience involving advanced statistical analysis;
Experience in work related to the analysis of statewide programs, including developmental disabilities or behavioral health services.



